Chinese chive pockets/dumplings 'éŸ­èœç›’å­' with crispy, chewy crust & a flavorful filling. By @woon.heng â£â € â €
â €
Recipe (makes ~9 palm size pockets)â£ ğŸŒ±Filling ingredientsâ£â €â €
~ 1/2 - 3/4 lb Chinese chive - cleaned, drained & finely choppedâ£â €â €
~ 8oz firm tofu - mashed, pan fried & seasoned with salt & white pepperâ£â €â €
~ 1 bundle mung bean thread - softened in hot water & cut into fine shredâ£â €â €
~ 1 tablespoon toasted sesame oilâ£â €â €
~ 1 1/2 teaspoons salt (adjust to your preference)â£â €â €
~ 1 teaspoon organic sugarâ£â €â €
~ a few shakes of white pepperâ£â €â €
â£â €â €
ğŸŒ±Dough ingredientsâ£â €â €
~ 2 3/4 cups all purpose flourâ£â €â €
~ 1/2 cup hot boiling waterâ£â €â €
~ 1/4 cup cold waterâ£â €â €
~ pinch of saltâ£â €â €
â£â €â €
âœ…To make the dough, place flour & salt in a mixing bowl, then gradually pour in boiling water into the dry ingredients while stirring continuously using a spatula/chopsticks. âœ…Continue adding cold water & knead into a soft dough, then let rest for 30 mins, covered.â£â €â €
âœ…Meanwhile, place chopped chive, mung bean thread & mashed tofu in a bowl. Season accordingly with toasted sesame oil, salt, sugar & white pepper (adjust taste accordingly).â£â €â €
âœ…To make the pockets, dust countertop with flour & divide dough into 9 pieces. Flatten each one with your palm & roll it into a circular disk by keeping the middle slightly thicker than the side. Fill each dough with fillings & pleat to seal by pinching the side.â£â €â €
âœ…In a heated non-stick/cast iron pan with a drizzle of oil, toast pockets until golden brown on all side over low-med heat (covered). Serve warm with sambal oelek.â£â €
